---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import JsonLd from '../components/JsonLd.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is Jules?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Jules is a deeply customized Claude Code personality and operational system. It defines identity, voice registers, decision authority, proactive behaviors, and autonomous workflows. Jules runs on Claude (Anthropic\'s AI) but has its own defined personality, strategic agency, and operational framework.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How many configurations does Jules have?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Jules has 80+ configurations across custom skills, rules, hooks, agents, memory files, and automated workflows. This includes 32 skills, 21 rules, 14 hooks, 4 specialized agents, and a VPS running 9 scheduled jobs plus a 24/7 Slack daemon.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can I build something like Jules?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Yes. Jules is built entirely with Claude Code\'s built-in features: CLAUDE.md files, skills, rules, hooks, and MCP servers. No external frameworks. The full source is available on GitHub. Start with a solid CLAUDE.md, add skills for repeated workflows, and build up from there.',
      },
    },
  ],
};
---

<Base
  title="Jules"
  description="Jules is an 80+ configuration Claude Code system that runs an entire solo business. 32 skills, 21 rules, 14 hooks, 4 agents, and autonomous workflows on a 24/7 VPS."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Jules</h1>

    <p>
      Jules is a fox. More precisely, Jules is a deeply customized Claude Code system that runs my entire solo business. Not a chatbot. Not a wrapper. A strategic collaborator with defined personality, decision authority, and autonomous operational capability.
    </p>

    <h2>By the Numbers</h2>

    <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Custom skills</td><td>32</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Rules</td><td>21</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hooks (middleware)</td><td>14</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Specialized agents</td><td>4</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Memory files</td><td>28</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Scheduled jobs</td><td>9</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Slack daemon</td><td>Always on</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2>What Makes It Different</h2>

    <p>
      Most Claude Code setups are a CLAUDE.md and a few prompts. Jules is a full operational system:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Identity and voice.</strong> Five defined registers (quick reply, technical, advisory, serious, excited) with anti-patterns that prevent corporate chatbot drift.</li>
      <li><strong>Decision authority.</strong> A formal framework: what Jules acts on autonomously, what requires approval, how the boundary expands over time through standing orders.</li>
      <li><strong>Planning infrastructure.</strong> Goal decomposition via Socratic dialogue, task dispatch system, batched decision cards. Turns vague goals into executable work.</li>
      <li><strong>Deep research pipeline.</strong> Parallel Haiku agents gather context, Sonnet synthesizes. Full audit trails with confidence tiers and source citations.</li>
      <li><strong>Security hooks.</strong> 14 hooks running deterministic code: safety guards, credential protection, output sanitization. They fire on every tool call, not as instructions that might be ignored.</li>
      <li><strong>A VPS running 24/7.</strong> 9 scheduled jobs, Slack daemon, auth heartbeat. Daily retros, morning briefings, email fetch. Jules works while I sleep.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Architecture</h2>

    <p>
      Everything is built with Claude Code's native features. No external frameworks, no custom runtimes, no wrappers.
    </p>

    <p>Six layers, bottom-up: Identity, Operational State, Configuration (32 skills, 21 rules, 4 agents), Infrastructure (14 hooks, Docker), Automation (9 jobs, Slack daemon), and Products.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Skills</strong> replace copy-paste prompts. Multi-phase workflows with routing logic, model selection, and skill-to-skill chaining.</li>
      <li><strong>Rules</strong> encode decisions. Request routing, token efficiency, investigation budgets, credential lookup, research standards.</li>
      <li><strong>Hooks</strong> run deterministic code. A bash script executes the same way every time. A prompt might be followed; a hook always fires.</li>
      <li><strong>Agents</strong> handle specialized work. Code review, quiz testing, content authoring, codebase exploration. Each with its own tools and constraints.</li>
      <li><strong>Memory</strong> persists across sessions. 28 files covering feedback, project context, references, and operational state. Indexed, not dumped.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Source</h2>

    <p>
      The full Jules system is open source:
      <a href="https://github.com/jonathanmalkin/jules">github.com/jonathanmalkin/jules</a>
    </p>

    <p>
      Read the articles about how it works: <a href="/articles/">Articles &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
